# Browserbase Persisted Context (dashboard side)

When a feature needs a workflow to stay logged in across scheduled runs, it needs a
Browserbase **Context**. Personal automations share ONE **account-level identity
context** per user/company; the dashboard's job is to resolve and store it. Auth
reliability is handled runner-side (see below).

## Do this
- For a **personal, user-owned** automation (eviivo, `/new` recorded, future personal scenarios), use the **identity context**: `ensureProfileBrowserbaseContextId(service, user)` returns the owner's `profiles.browserbase_context_id` (company-or-user) and stamps it onto the `automations.browserbase_context_id` row (see `ensureHospitalityAutomation`). Never lazily create a new context per run/save — inconsistent ids silently break persistence (the next run starts logged out).
- **Gov monitors are the exception:** they are org/`gov_profile`-scoped and keep their **dedicated per-scenario** contexts (`workflow_browser_contexts`), with their own reset/login lifecycle. Do NOT route them through the identity context.

## The identity context (company-or-user), frozen on the profile
- One account context per identity, **frozen on `profiles.browserbase_context_id`** the first time it's needed: a corporate user (work-email domain) inherits the **earliest teammate's** context for that domain; a consumer/free-email user gets their own. See `ensureProfileBrowserbaseContextId` in `src/lib/new-automation/recording-context.js`. Used by the `/new` recorder session AND eviivo runs (and future personal scenarios), so a single login covers them all.
- Provision with the **service role** — corporate teammates live in other users' `profiles` rows that per-user RLS hides. Uses the **one** helper (`createBrowserbaseContext`); no separate context table.
- The recording session runs with `browserSettings.context = { id, persist: true }` (see `createBrowserbaseSession`); the same id is stamped onto `automations.browserbase_context_id`. On the runner, identity scenarios (eviivo, `custom_recorded_automation`) resolve the context from `profiles.browserbase_context_id` (source of truth) and **never** fall back to the per-scenario `workflow_browser_contexts` (all recorded automations share one scenario id → that would leak one login jar across tenants).
- **Egress pinning must match the runner.** The recording session pins region + Browserbase proxy + viewport via `resolveIdentitySessionPinning()` (`BROWSERBASE_IDENTITY_*` env, proxies default ON, viewport `1920x1080`). The cookies a user creates while logging in are minted under that egress; the runner reuses the SAME identity pin for both `/new` and eviivo runs (its identity pin reads `BROWSERBASE_IDENTITY_*` then `BROWSERBASE_EVIIVO_*`). **Ops:** these are two separate deployments (Vercel + Lambda) — set the identity `BROWSERBASE_*` values identically in both, or leave defaults (they match). If they drift, login-bound sites reject the restored context.
- **Captcha split matches eviivo.** The recording session is a human-driven login (like `scripts/eviivo_login.py`), so it passes `solveCaptchas: false` — the real login challenge must render for the person to solve; auto-solving a login Turnstile submits a token the site rejects. Scheduled runs leave `solveCaptchas` at the Browserbase default (on) to clear the bot-check unattended.
- **Tradeoff of one shared jar:** a context reset/bot-flag for an identity wipes **every** login for that identity at once (eviivo + everything), and the identity's single egress pin must satisfy all its automations. Accepted deliberately to centralize logins.

## Know this
- A Context persists **cookies + localStorage only — NOT sessionStorage**. A freshly created context is an **empty cookie jar**: automated runs will NOT be authenticated until a human completes the first login once via Live View (runner's `scripts/eviivo_login.py`). Build the UX to surface/allow that first login, and don't treat "context created" as "logged in".
- Don't build a second context-creation path or stash the id elsewhere — one helper (`createBrowserbaseContext`), one column (`automations.browserbase_context_id`).

## Reliability lives in the runner (don't reinvent here)
For login-walled sources, IP/fingerprint **pinning**, the **captcha split** (auto-solve on for automated runs, off for manual login), and the **/login → dashboard reload-to-redirect** are all handled in `chromie-runner` / `chromie-tools`. See their `.cursor/rules` (`browserbase-persisted-auth`, `browser-tool-auth-and-scraping`) before assuming a context alone is enough. If the site binds sessions to IP/fingerprint, the context must be paired with runner-side pinning or restored cookies get rejected.
